The Treasury Returns to the Bond Market Amid Stable Interest Rates: Implications for Spain’s Real Estate Sector

This article is for informational purposes only and does not constitute investment advice or a recommendation in any form.

Spain’s Public Treasury will resume its regular bond auctions next week in a climate of monetary stability and renewed confidence in the European Central Bank’s (ECB) policy direction. Following its meeting on 30 October 2025, the ECB, led by Christine Lagarde, decided to keep all three key rates unchanged: the deposit facility at 2.00%, the main refinancing rate at 2.15%, and the marginal lending facility at 2.40%. The message was clear — inflation is approaching the 2% target, and monetary policy will remain in a cautious, data-dependent stance.

According to the official calendar released by the Ministry of Economy, the Treasury will hold three- and nine-month bill auctions on 11 November and bond and obligation issues on 20 November. These operations aim to refinance part of Spain’s public debt at historically low yields for this phase of the cycle, capitalizing on strong institutional investor demand. In the secondary market, the yield on Spain’s 10-year government bond stands at around 3.16%, well below the 4.1% peak reached in 2023.

This stabilization extends beyond sovereign debt markets. For the real estate sector, the performance of Spanish government bonds serves as a reference for funding costs across the economy — from developers and investment funds to individual borrowers. With the end of the ECB’s rate-hiking cycle, mortgage rates are beginning to stabilize, restoring predictability to project margins. The improvement in financing conditions is breathing life back into residential development, where demand remains solid across Spain’s major cities.

The yield spread between sovereign debt and real estate assets remains significant. According to Idealista, Spain’s average gross rental yield stood at 6.9% in the third quarter of 2025, reaching 7.4% in Madrid and 8.3% in Barcelona. This positive differential compared with long-term government bonds reinforces real estate’s status as an attractive, yield-bearing asset in an environment of moderate inflation.

Still, the sector faces persistent structural challenges. Construction costs have risen by 27.5% since 2020, according to UVE Valoraciones, due to higher material and energy prices. Combined with a shortage of developable land, these pressures continue to push up new-home prices, which reached €2,093 per square meter, the highest level since 2008, according to the Ministry of Housing. Supply shortages and lengthy approval times remain the main bottlenecks to easing affordability pressures.

Despite these headwinds, real estate investment has regained momentum. Data from CBRE’s Real Estate Market Outlook 2025 show that investment volumes reached €12.9 billion in the first nine months of 2025, a 44% year-on-year increase, making it the third-strongest year on record. The recovery has been driven by build-to-rent housing, logistics facilities, and renewed international interest in Spanish assets. Stable financing conditions have allowed many delayed transactions to move forward again.

At the same time, digitalization is reshaping how capital flows into the property sector. The growth of crowdfunding and crowdlending platforms provides an alternative channel for individual investors to participate directly in real estate projects, bypassing traditional intermediaries. These models combine transparency, traceability, and access to tangible assets — often with yields that remain competitive against sovereign debt.

